thread.title: $A bounces off its six-year low

title: $A bounces off its six-year low
text:
Print 
The Australian dollar is quickly bouncing back from six year lows, shrugging off falls on global share markets. 
At 1200 AEST on Tuesday, the currency was trading at 72.04 US cents, down from 72.36 cents on Monday, but up on the low of 70.44 US cents hit overnight. 
The local share market is up more than two per and most Asian markets are also stronger, recovering from Monday's steep falls. 
LTG GoldRock director Andrew Barnett said buyers started coming it once the Australian dollar got close to 70 US cents. 
"It's not unusual to see a rebound like this on the Aussie as the exhaustion factor takes over and people go bargain hunting," he said. 
"I still think we're likely to see over the coming month or two the Aussie dollar back under 70 US cents, 68 cents is my target." 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* 72.04 US cents, from 72.36 cents on Monday 
* 86.34 Japanese yen, from 87.55 yen 
* 62.44 euro cents, from 63.13 euro cents 
* 110.77 New Zealand cents, from 109.65 NZ cents 
* 45.74 British pence, from 46.26 pence 
Government bond yields: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.748pct, from 1.695pct on Monday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.671pct, from 2.569pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* The September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.375 (implying a yield of 2.625 per cent), down from 97.470 (2.530 per cent) on Monday. 
* The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.240 (1.760 per cent), down from 98.300 (1.700 per cent). 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session, bond market closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
